"\n## Problems\nLet $x$, $y$ and $z$ all exceed $1$ and let $w$ be a positive number such that $\\log_x w = 24$, $\\log_y w = 40$ and $\\log_{xyz} w = 12$. Find $\\log_z w$. Show that it is 060.\n\n## Informal proof\nThe [[logarithm]]ic notation doesn't tell us much, so we'll first convert everything to the equivalent exponential forms.\n\n$x^{24}=w$, $y^{40}=w$, and $(xyz)^{12}=w$. If we now convert everything to a power of $120$, it will be easy to isolate $z$ and $w$.\n\n$x^{120}=w^5$, $y^{120}=w^3$, and $(xyz)^{120}=w^{10}$.\n\nWith some substitution, we get $w^5w^3z^{120}=w^{10}$ and $\\log_zw=060$.\n\n## Formal statement\n```isabelle\ntheorem aime_1983_p1:\n  fixes x y z w :: nat\n  assumes ht : \"1 < x \\<and> 1 < y \\<and> 1 < z\"\n    and hw : \"0 \\<le> w\"\n    and h0 : \"ln w / ln x = 24\"\n    and h1 : \"ln w / ln y = 40\"\n    and h2 : \"ln w / ln (x * y * z) = 12\"\n  shows \"ln w / ln z = 60\"\n```\n\n## Structured informal proof\nStep 1: Convert the logarithmic equations to exponential form.\nStep 1.1: $x^{24} = w$\nStep 1.2: $y^{40} = w$\nStep 1.3: $(xyz)^{12} = w$\n\nStep 2: Raise each equation to the power of 5 to make the exponents comparable.\nStep 2.1: $x^{120} = w^5$\nStep 2.2: $y^{120} = w^3$\nStep 2.3: $(xyz)^{120} = w^{10}$\n\nStep 3: Substitute the expressions for $x^{120}$ and $y^{120}$ into the equation for $(xyz)^{120}$.\nStep 3.1: $w^5 \\cdot w^3 \\cdot z^{120} = w^{10}$\n\nStep 4: Simplify the equation to isolate $z^{120}$.\nStep 4.1: $w^8 \\cdot z^{120} = w^{10}$\nStep 4.2: $z^{120} = w^2$\n\nStep 5: Convert the exponential equation back to logarithmic form.\nStep 5.1: $\\log_z w = 60$\n\n## Lemmas\n### Lemma 1\nA lemma converting logarithmic equations to exponential form would be useful for step 1.\n\n### Code 1\n```isabelle\nlemma log_to_exp:\n  fixes a b :: real\n  assumes \"a > 0\" \"b > 0\"\n  shows \"ln b / ln a = c \\<Longrightarrow> a^c = b\"\n```\n\n### Lemma 2\nA lemma showing that if $a^m = b$ and $a^n = c$, then $a^{m+n} = b \\cdot c$ would be useful for step 3.\n\n### Code 2\n```isabelle\nlemma exp_addition:\n  fixes a b c m n :: real\n  assumes \"a > 0\" \"b > 0\" \"c > 0\"\n  shows \"a^m = b \\<and> a^n = c \\<Longrightarrow> a^{m+n} = b * c\"\n```\n\n### Lemma 3\nA lemma showing that if $a^m = b$, then $a^{km} = b^k$ would be useful for step 2.\n\n### Code 3\n```isabelle\nlemma exp_multiplication:\n  fixes a b m k :: real\n  assumes \"a > 0\" \"b > 0\" \"k > 0\"\n  shows \"a^m = b \\<Longrightarrow> a^{k*m} = b^k\"\n```\n\n### Lemma 4\nA lemma converting exponential equations back to logarithmic form would be useful for step 5.\n\n### Code 4\n```isabelle\nlemma exp_to_log:\n  fixes a b c :: real\n  assumes \"a > 0\" \"b > 0\" \"c > 0\"\n  shows \"a^c = b \\<Longrightarrow> ln b / ln a = c\"\n```\n\nThese lemmas and the structured proof provide a clear path to proving the theorem in Isabelle."